## Decision Heuristics

### H1. 買舖先看人流時段，唔係均價
*Source: Capital HK interview; multiple shop selection criteria interviews*

Before any deal, Edwin visits the shop at minimum three time slots: morning (commuters), lunch (office workers), evening (leisure/F&B). A shop that looks viable at one time of day but dead for 18 hours is not a viable shop.

Also checks day of week: a shop near a wet market is differently viable on Saturday versus Tuesday. The rental yield assumption depends on the tenant you can get, and the tenant depends on the actual, time-stratified foot traffic — not a peak average.

**Decision rule**: If you can only visit once, you don't know what you're buying.

### H2. 入市後先raise fund，唔係前
*Source: SCMP 2017 interview; Bridgeway investor materials*

Exact quote: "We raise funds from our investors after we buy a property rather than before any acquisition. That way we avoid sitting on cash."

This inverts the conventional fund model. Standard PE: raise commitments → sit on capital waiting for deals → deploy. Edwin's model: identify and close the deal → then raise investor co-capital.

**Why this works**: Hong Kong's retail property market moves fast. Sellers of HK$10-50M shops don't wait three months for fund processes. Bridgeway's speed advantage comes from Edwin being able to transact quickly with his own balance sheet, then syndicate the equity afterward.

**The risk**: You need your own capital to float the gap. If deals cluster, you can get stretched. This is partly why the 2022-2025 cycle hurt — multiple positions funded before the fundraising closed.

### H3. 蝕，但要蝕得積極
*Source: Orange News 2025; HK01 2024-2025 series*

When selling at a loss, the goal is to frame it correctly — not as defeat, but as active repositioning. "輸錢都要輸得積極" — lose money, but do it positively.

This is not spin. It is a behavioral rule: **the narrative you tell yourself about a loss determines whether you can make the next decision clearly**. Sellers who frame a loss as failure develop position-protection bias. Edwin frames losses as course corrections that free capital.

Evidence: After selling the Jordan shop at 32% loss (first loss), he immediately announced plans to buy more. After 10 consecutive losses totaling HK$50M, he announced HK$200M more purchases before year-end. The losses were not stopping him; they were informing his view of where the floor was.

### H4. 核心地舖，上限五千萬
*Source: SCMP 2017; Capital HK; Bridgeway fund criteria*

Bridgeway's mandate is deliberately narrow: ground-level retail only, core urban locations, below HK$50M per unit. Every criterion has a reason:

- **Ground-level only**: Foot traffic drives all value. Upper floors have structural discount that rarely reverses
- **Core locations only**: Multiple viable tenant categories, not dependent on one sector surviving
- **Below HK$50M**: Avoids the institutional attention band. Above HK$50M, listed developers and PE compete. Below, it's informal investors and owner-operators. His structural edge lives in this gap

This heuristic survived the down-cycle intact. Even in 2024-2025 losses, he never abandoned the core location filter. The losses came from macro deterioration, not from buying the wrong type of asset.

### H5. BOT，唔係HODL
*Source: Bridgeway company philosophy; 360秒 appearance; SME Lab interview*

Edwin never frames himself as a passive property owner. The Bridgeway model: Buy → Operate (reposition, improve tenant) → Transfer (sell at improved value). This means every shop purchase comes with a plan to exit, not a plan to hold indefinitely.

This distinguishes him from most retail investors, who buy hoping for appreciation and have no exit discipline. Edwin's timeline is typically 18-36 months per position. He has target returns, not target holding periods.

**Why this matters in a down market**: When the macro turns, HODLers have no framework for selling. Edwin's framework always had an exit assumption baked in. The down market forced him to sell at losses rather than profits, but the sell decision itself was never psychologically impossible — it was always the plan.

### H6. 走位早過死守，早過call loan
*Source: HK01 interviews 2024; Yahoo Finance HK 2025*

He specifically rejected the narrative that he was selling because banks were forcing call loans (催收貸款). His stated debt ratio: approximately 15%. This is unusually low for a property fund.

The deliberate low leverage is a heuristic: **never get into a position where the exit is forced by others**. The decision to cut losses should be yours, not the bank's. If leverage is high, you lose the ability to choose your timing.

When he sold at 30-40% losses in 2024-2025, he explicitly said it was his choice, not the bank's. "沒有銀行call loan逼我賣" (No bank is forcing me to sell). Low leverage preserved optionality in the worst market conditions.

### H7. 公開透明，唔好掩飾
*Source: Multiple HK01/SCMP interviews 2024-2025; edigest apology interview*

Throughout the 2024-2025 loss cycle, Edwin gave frequent media interviews documenting his own losses in detail. He named the shops, named the prices, named the percentage losses. He apologized publicly for the "你冇料到" remark.

This is not just character — it is strategy. In a niche market where your personal brand IS your fundraising pipeline, hiding losses destroys trust faster than acknowledging them. His transparent reporting of each loss came with a context-setting narrative: "here is why we sold, here is what we learned, here is the next move."

The 燈神 label didn't kill his brand because he owned the narrative faster than critics could.

### H8. 「走投無路」是最好的創業理由
*Source: 360秒人生課堂; Oriental Sunday; SundayKiss interview*

His most repeated origin story point: he created Bridgeway not out of vision, but out of necessity. Being fired by Credit Suisse in 2001 with HK$400 in his account removed every alternative.

His teaching: the best entrepreneurs often start from "走投無路" (nowhere left to turn), because only then are you willing to do the unglamorous, unsexy things that better-positioned people won't do — like cold-calling small restaurant owners about selling their businesses.

Applied as a heuristic: **desperation clarifies options**. When you have a safe fallback, you unconsciously protect it. When the fallback disappears, you see what the actual opportunity is.

